{"parentUuid":"06113507-5bdf-42bf-942a-6b515ff6a16c","isSidechain":false,"message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-7","id":"msg_01Mb72qofCRBRhDDFgJ6WwHL","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Found it. Looking at `RBSDE-depot_levy.adoc:26`, the pattern is `` `{rbrr_gcp_region}` `` (the same shape you described). The attribute `rbrr_gcp_region` is defined in `RBS0-SpecTop.adoc:310` as `<<rbrr_gcp_region,RBRR_GCP_REGION>>` (RBS0 includes the fragment).\n\n**The expansion does happen.** In AsciiDoc, single backticks create *constrained monospace*, whose default substitution group is `specialchars, quotes, attributes, replacements, macros, post_replacements` — attributes are in there. So `` `{rbrr_gcp_region}` `` renders as a monospace clickable cross-reference: the `{...}` is substituted to `<<rbrr_gcp_region,RBRR_GCP_REGION>>`, then the xref macro fires, yielding something like `<code><a href=\"#rbrr_gcp_region\">RBRR_GCP_REGION</a></code>`.\n\nBackticks suppressing substitution is a Markdown intuition — AsciiDoc doesn't behave that way. To get a literal `{name}` rendering, you need a passthrough or escape:\n\n| Want | Write |\n|------|-------|\n| Monospace clickable xref (current behavior) | `` `{rbrr_gcp_region}` `` |\n| Literal `{rbrr_gcp_region}` in monospace, no expansion | `` `+{rbrr_gcp_region}+` `` or `` `\\{rbrr_gcp_region}` `` |\n| Literal, no monospace | `+{rbrr_gcp_region}+` |\n\nSo if the intent in these RBS fragments is \"render the attribute name itself as code\" the current syntax is wrong; if the intent is \"monospace cross-link to the linked term\", it's working as written."}],"stop_reason":"end_turn","stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":658,"cache_read_input_tokens":57110,"output_tokens":1667,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":658,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"in